README.md
     1→# color
     3→Color lets you use colorized outputs in terms of [ANSI Escape
     4→Codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANSI_escape_code#Colors) in Go (Golang). It
     5→has support for Windows too! The API can be used in several ways, pick one that
     6→suits you.
     7→
     8→![Color](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/438920/96832689-03b3e000-13f4-11eb-9803-46f4c4de3406.jpg)
     9→
    10→## Install
    12→```
    13→go get github.com/fatih/color
    14→```
    15→
    16→## Examples
    18→### Standard colors
    20→```go
    21→// Print with default helper functions
    22→color.Cyan("Prints text in cyan.")
    23→
    24→// A newline will be appended automatically
    25→color.Blue("Prints %s in blue.", "text")
    26→
    27→// These are using the default foreground colors
    28→color.Red("We have red")
    29→color.Magenta("And many others ..")
    30→
    31→```
    32→
    33→### RGB colors
    35→If your terminal supports 24-bit colors, you can use RGB color codes.
    36→
    37→```go
    38→color.RGB(255, 128, 0).Println("foreground orange")
    39→color.RGB(230, 42, 42).Println("foreground red")
    40→
    41→color.BgRGB(255, 128, 0).Println("background orange")
    42→color.BgRGB(230, 42, 42).Println("background red")
    43→```
    44→
    45→### Mix and reuse colors
    47→```go
    48→// Create a new color object
    49→c := color.New(color.FgCyan).Add(color.Underline)
    50→c.Println("Prints cyan text with an underline.")
    51→
    52→// Or just add them to New()
    53→d := color.New(color.FgCyan, color.Bold)
    54→d.Printf("This prints bold cyan %s\n", "too!.")
    55→
    56→// Mix up foreground and background colors, create new mixes!
    57→red := color.New(color.FgRed)
    58→
    59→boldRed := red.Add(color.Bold)
    60→boldRed.Println("This will print text in bold red.")
    61→
    62→whiteBackground := red.Add(color.BgWhite)
    63→whiteBackground.Println("Red text with white background.")
    64→
    65→// Mix with RGB color codes
      →…
    71→### Use your own output (io.Writer)
    73→```go
    74→// Use your own io.Writer output
    75→color.New(color.FgBlue).Fprintln(myWriter, "blue color!")
    76→
    77→blue := color.New(color.FgBlue)
    78→blue.Fprint(writer, "This will print text in blue.")
    79→```
    80→
    81→### Custom print functions (PrintFunc)
    83→```go
    84→// Create a custom print function for convenience
    85→red := color.New(color.FgRed).PrintfFunc()
    86→red("Warning")
    87→red("Error: %s", err)
    88→
    89→// Mix up multiple attributes
    90→notice := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).PrintlnFunc()
    91→notice("Don't forget this...")
    92→```
    93→
    94→### Custom fprint functions (FprintFunc)
    96→```go
    97→blue := color.New(color.FgBlue).FprintfFunc()
    98→blue(myWriter, "important notice: %s", stars)
    99→
   100→// Mix up with multiple attributes
   101→success := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).FprintlnFunc()
   102→success(myWriter, "Don't forget this...")
   103→```
   104→
   105→### Insert into noncolor strings (SprintFunc)
   107→```go
   108→// Create SprintXxx functions to mix strings with other non-colorized strings:
   109→yellow := color.New(color.FgYellow).SprintFunc()
   110→red := color.New(color.FgRed).SprintFunc()
   111→fmt.Printf("This is a %s and this is %s.\n", yellow("warning"), red("error"))
   112→
   113→info := color.New(color.FgWhite, color.BgGreen).SprintFunc()
   114→fmt.Printf("This %s rocks!\n", info("package"))
   115→
   116→// Use helper functions
   117→fmt.Println("This", color.RedString("warning"), "should be not neglected.")
   118→fmt.Printf("%v %v\n", color.GreenString("Info:"), "an important message.")
   119→
   120→// Windows supported too! Just don't forget to change the output to color.Output
   121→fmt.Fprintf(color.Output, "Windows support: %s", color.GreenString("PASS"))
   122→```
   123→
   124→### Plug into existing code
   126→```go
   127→// Use handy standard colors
   128→color.Set(color.FgYellow)
   129→
   130→fmt.Println("Existing text will now be in yellow")
   131→fmt.Printf("This one %s\n", "too")
   132→
   133→color.Unset() // Don't forget to unset
   134→
   135→// You can mix up parameters
   136→color.Set(color.FgMagenta, color.Bold)
   137→defer color.Unset() // Use it in your function
   138→
   139→fmt.Println("All text will now be bold magenta.")
   140→```
   141→
   142→### Disable/Enable color
   144→There might be a case where you want to explicitly disable/enable color output. the 
   145→`go-isatty` package will automatically disable color output for non-tty output streams 
   146→(for example if the output were piped directly to `less`).
   147→
   148→The `color` package also disables color output if the [`NO_COLOR`](https://no-color.org) environment
   149→variable is set to a non-empty string.
   150→
   151→`Color` has support to disable/enable colors programmatically both globally and
   152→for single color definitions. For example suppose you have a CLI app and a
   153→`-no-color` bool flag. You can easily disable the color output with:
   154→
   155→```go
   156→var flagNoColor = flag.Bool("no-color", false, "Disable color output")
   157→
   158→if *flagNoColor {
   159→	color.NoColor = true // disables colorized output
   160→}
   161→```
   162→
      →…
   177→## GitHub Actions
   179→To output color in GitHub Actions (or other CI systems that support ANSI colors), make sure to set `color.NoColor = false` so that it bypasses the check for non-tty output streams. 
   180→
   181→
